lear pleomorphism, loss of nuclear polarity, and frequent mitotic figures. There is evidence of desmoplastic stromal response surrounding the glandular elements.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adenocarcinoma in situ","Invasive adenocarcinoma","Invasive squamous cell carcinoma","Lichen sclerosus","Squamous cell carcinoma in situ"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe microscopic features described are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Einvasive adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the cervix. The key diagnostic features include irregular glandular structures invading the stroma with associated desmoplastic response, nuclear atypia, and increased mitotic activity.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenocarcinoma in situ\u003C/strong\u003E shows atypical glandular cells but is confined to the surface epithelium without stromal invasion. \u003Cstrong\u003EInvasive squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows invasion of abnormal squamous cells rather than glandular elements. \u003Cstrong\u003ELichen sclerosus\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates thinned epithelium with underlying hyalinised collagen. \u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma in situ\u003C/strong\u003E shows full-thickness dysplasia of squamous epithelium without invasion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cervical adenocarcinoma shows irregular glandular structures with complex architecture invading the stroma","Nuclear atypia, loss of polarity, and increased mitotic figures are key microscopic features of cervical adenocarcinoma","Cervical adenocarcinoma arises from the glandular epithelium of the endocervix"],"references":["Takeuchi S. Biology and treatment of cervical adenocarcinoma. Chin J Cancer Res. 2016 Apr;28(2):254-62. doi: 10.21147/j.issn.1000-9604.2016.02.11. PMID: 27198186; PMCID: PMC4865619.","Oku